  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Anyang Temple
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Accompanying the moon, we climbed Anyang Tower,
    Then sent a friend off toward the clear stream's play.
    We scattered a lean horse to cry upon the grassland,
    And pitched a small white canopy at the ferry crossing.

    Every traveler we met asked where you were bound—
    "Did you leave the riverside pavilion this very dawn?"
    Suddenly we spotted a weary servant driving a stubborn donkey,
    Jacket loosened, a zither strapped across his straining shoulders.

    Here comes a youth in straw sandals and rough travel clothes,
    The very last to arrive—surely that must be you!
    We bowed once and broke into uproarious laughter,
    Then waded barefoot into the stream in our short pants,

    Casting our net we caught silver-scaled fish,
    Scaled them, sliced them fine, seasoned with wild greens.
    Though praise and blame swirl about us endlessly,
    Your heart turns toward the mountains—unforgotten.

    The city forbids wine as strictly as theft;
    The market's revelers dwindle, few drunk faces remain.
    How many friends are left to share a final cup?
    We sit together, wringing out our joy, our hats askew.

    Now that you head south, when will you return?
    The dark clouds and spring trees stretch so far away.
    If leisure finds you in your garden's quiet ways,
    Send new poems often, mounted on scrolls for the moon to see.
  footnotes:
    - Anyang Temple was a famous Buddhist temple near Seoul known for its scenic location and as a gathering place for literati.
    - The image of the barefoot youth in rough clothes represents freedom from worldly concerns and official rank, central to the literati ideal.
    - The prohibition on wine likely refers to a specific historical period when alcohol sales were restricted in Seoul.
    - Moon scrolls (월축) were decorative hanging scrolls featuring poems or calligraphy, meant to be appreciated seasonally.
